⚠️ 8. Problems with Spin Locks
    1. CPU Wastage

        Thread burns CPU cycles doing nothing

    2. Starvation

        One thread may never get lock

    3. No fairness

No guarantee of order

🚀 9. Optimized Spin (Backoff Strategy)

    Instead of tight loop:

        while (!lock.compareAndSet(false, true)) {
            Thread.onSpinWait(); // Java 9+
        }

        Or:

        while (!lock.compareAndSet(false, true)) {
            try {
                Thread.sleep(1); // backoff
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {}
        }

🧠 1. Why Pure Spin Locks Are Rare in Java

A pure spin lock (like we wrote earlier) is too naive for real systems:

    ❌ Wastes CPU if lock is held longer
    ❌ No fairness
    ❌ Doesn’t scale with many threads

    👉 So Java uses hybrid approaches:

    Spin for a short time → then block (park thread)

⚙️ 2. Hybrid Locking (Spin + Block)
👉 Strategy:
    Try to acquire lock using CAS
    If fails → spin briefly
    If still fails → block (park thread)

🔄 Flow
    Try CAS → Success → Done
        ↓
     Fail → Spin (few iterations)
        ↓
     Still fail → Park (sleep)

🧪 Example (Conceptual)

    while (!tryAcquire()) {
        for (int i = 0; i < SPIN_LIMIT; i++) {
            if (tryAcquire()) return;
        }
        park(); // block thread
    }